Naa10 het heart

Naa10 heterozygous mutant (+/- or +/-) heart lysate analysis

Hearts were obtained from biological replicates of Naa10 heterozygous mutants (+/- or -/+; n = 3) and wild-type controls (+/+; n = 3). Each biological replicate was assayed twice.

Fresh or thawed flash-frozen tissue were lysed in RIPA buffer supplemented with protease inhibitor tablets (Sigma-Aldrich, #R0278; Roche #11836153001). Tissue was homogenized using a handheld motorized microtube pestle. Lysate was then cleared after centrifugation (15,000 rcf, 20 minutes). Total protein was quantified using Advanced Protein Assay Reagent (Cytoskeleton Inc., #ADV02). Lysate was then diluted in 2X SDS-PAGE Sample Buffer (5% v/v 2-mercaptoethanol) and heated (95 - 100C, 5 minutes).

20 g of protein were resolved on a a 10% mini-PROTEAN TGX gel (Bio-Rad, #4561033). SDS-PAGE gel was equilibrated in chilled Towbins transfer buffer. Proteins were transferred from gel to 0.2 m nitrocellulose membrane (Amersham) at 100V, 30 minutes under refrigeration. After transfer, membrane was allowed to dry at least 1 hour. Membranes were stained for transfer verification and total protein sing REVERT 700 total protein stain (Li-cor, #926-11015).

After stain removal, membrane was blocked in TBS with 5% non-fat dry milk (1 hr, RT). After decanting blocking buffer, membrane was incubated (overnight, 4C) in 1/500 anti-NAA10 (diluted in blocking buffer supplemented with 0.1% v/v Tween-20). Membrane was then washed 5 minutes in TBS-T for 3 repetitions. Membrane was then incubated (1 hr, RT) using 1/20000 goat-anti-rabbit IR800 CW (Li-cor, 926-32211). Membrane was again washed 5 minutes in TBS-T for 3 repetitions and then briefly rinsed in TBS. Membrane was allowed to dry before imaging.

Immunostained membranes were imaged on Odyssey Classic (Li-cor). Analysis was conducted and plotted using Empiria Studio (Li-cor) and R.

#the successive geom_point plots the mean; specify color so it does not conflict with the color call in the first geom_point

ggplot(heart,aes(x = Genotype,
                 y = Normalized.Signal))+
  stat_summary(fun= mean, geom="point",
               shape=3, size=5, color="red", fill="black")+
  geom_errorbar(data = heart_sum1,
                aes(ymin = Normalized.Signal-sd,
                    ymax = Normalized.Signal+sd,
                    width = 0.25))+
    geom_boxplot(outlier.shape = NA,
               alpha = 0.1)+
  geom_point(aes(color = Name,
                 shape = Replicate),
             alpha = 1,
                 position = position_jitterdodge())+
  xlab("Naa10 genotype")+

       REVERT total protein stain")+
  ggtitle("")

#hypothesis testing ##parametric ###two-sample t-test null hypothesis: there is no mean difference in NAA10 signal between Naa10 female genotypes

Alternative: there is a difference in NAA10 signal between Naa10 female genotypes

##Unpaired t-test of NAA10 signal grouped by Genotype
t.test(heart$Normalized.Signal~heart$Genotype,
       paired = F,
       var.equal = F)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  heart$Normalized.Signal by heart$Genotype
## t = -3.4585, df = 10.173, p-value = 0.005986
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means between group Naa10 +/- or -/+ and group Naa10 +/+ is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -179467.51  -39026.63
## sample estimates:
## mean in group Naa10 +/- or -/+        mean in group Naa10 +/+ 
##                       54519.94                      163767.01

I fail to reject the null hypothesis

##non-parametric testing ###NAA10 signal and Genotype I have a big outlier in each genotype, so I will perform non-parametric hypothesis tests in addition to

#Wilcox test instead of Welch's t-test
wilcox.test(Normalized.Signal~Genotype,heart)
## 
##  Wilcoxon rank sum exact test
## 
## data:  Normalized.Signal by Genotype
## W = 16, p-value = 0.03147
## alternative hypothesis: true location shift is not equal to 0

p = 0.03; I reject the null hypothesis.

###Does replicate blot drive differences in NAA10 signal

kruskal.test(Normalized.Signal~Replicate,heart)
## 
##  Kruskal-Wallis rank sum test
## 
## data:  Normalized.Signal by Replicate
## Kruskal-Wallis chi-squared = 10.152, df = 2, p-value = 0.006245

I reject the null hypothesis.
